<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-088-131 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 205 133</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 1 1991 n1273 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why the human factor is central to IT success. (informationtechnology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mckerrow, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Missed opportunities in the information technology (IT) world aredue largely to deficiencies in managerial enterprise.andP;  Anyone whobelieves technological issues are key to the success of IT ismisled.andP;  More demanding human issues are primary issues; technicalissues are secondary.andP;  The elementary step is to recognize thecentrality of human efforts within IT.andP;  Problems associated withdeployment and management of the new technology are critical.andP;  ITsuccess will depend largely on how well the demands andrequirements placed on employees are handled when an organizationchanges from a centralized facility to a smaller, end-usercontrolled facility.andP;  A different set of values and controls iscalled for in order to manage an end-user controlled shop.andP;  ITmanagers need a combination of business, technical andinterpersonal skills.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Human FactorsManagement StyleMISInformation Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>